<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06161077 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06161077 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: New York Times; Slim, sun-face thongs from Unisa  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  FASHION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  AFTER being closed up in pumps and booties all winter, women's feet can take abreather this summer. Sandals that reveal the toes and mules that liberate theheels are the styles of choice. And the barer the better.;    For day, sandalsand mules are on flat or curvy low heels. But for evening, high heels make asexy statement when toes are bare.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WINTER-WEARY FEET BREATHE EASY IN LIBERATINGSANDALS AND MULES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Style  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;People want fun styles, anything opened up, sling-backs or sexy strappyshoes,&quot; said Irenka Jakubiak, Lord andamp; Taylor's fashion director of footwear.&quot;Thongs are our No. 1 sellers, and metallics are very strong, not just forevening but for day and sporty occasions, too.&quot;;    Sandals have long beenassociated with summer, but mules have made a strong comeback thanks to ManoloBlahnik, who designed flat and curved-heel versions for Isaac Mizrahi's springshow.;    &quot;Up until this season, mules or slides had been a novelty, but nowthey're really selling,&quot; said Barbara Warner, Bergdorf Goodman's generalmerchandise manager.;    The most casual summer shoes of all are thongs, whichare no longer just for the beach. Bergdorf's has Ferragamo's thong sandals inwhite, black or tan leather decorated with antique-looking buttons ($150), andvery bare asymmetric thongs of gold and silver cord wound together ($75).;   Whatever you pay for thongs or sandals, for the ultimate in warm-weather cool,they should be worn with bare legs.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910609  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.CO